Sure, I can try to load the URL via the GitHub GraphQL API. The GitHub GraphQL API is a flexible and powerful way to query data from GitHub, as you can see from the web search results I provided¹². However, loading a specific URL via the GraphQL API is not as straightforward as using the REST API, because GraphQL does not use URLs to identify resources. Instead, GraphQL uses a schema-based query language that allows you to specify the exact data you want to fetch¹.

To load the URL you gave me, which is https://github.com/meta-introspector/meta-meme/issues/51#issuecomment-1686397633, we need to break it down into its components and map them to the corresponding GraphQL types and fields. The URL consists of:

- The base URL: https://github.com
- The owner name: meta-introspector
- The repository name: meta-meme
- The issue number: 51
- The comment ID: 1686397633

The base URL is not relevant for the GraphQL API, so we can ignore it. The owner name and the repository name can be used to query for a repository object using the repository field on the Query root type¹. The issue number can be used to query for an issue object using the issue field on the Repository type¹. The comment ID can be used to query for a comment object using the node field on the Query root type¹. However, the comment ID is not the same as the global node ID that GraphQL expects, so we need to convert it first. We can do this by appending MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2ODYzOTc2MzM= to the base64-encoded string IssueComment , which is the type name of the comment object¹. This gives us MDExOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2ODYzOTc2MzM= as the global node ID.

Now that we have all the components we need, we can construct a GraphQL query that will load the data from the URL. Here is an example of such a query:

query {
  repository(owner: "meta-introspector", name: "meta-meme") {
    issue(number: 51) {
      title
      body
      author {
        login
      }
    }
  }
  node(id: "MDExOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2ODYzOTc2MzM=") {
    ... on IssueComment {
      body
      author {
        login
      }
    }
  }
}

This query will return the title, body, and author login of both the issue and the comment that correspond to the URL. You can try running this query in the GraphQL Explorer¹ or using any other GraphQL client of your choice. I hope this helps you understand how to load a URL via the GitHub GraphQL API better. 😊

