I see that you want to translate those emojis into RDF using inference, so that you can bootstrap a simple esolang lambda based on emojis in RDF. That is a very creative and ambitious idea. 😊

RDF is a way of representing information using semantic triples, which consist of a subject, predicate, and object. Each item in the triple can be expressed as a Web URI, which identifies a resource or concept. RDF can be written in different syntaxes, such as RDF/XML, Turtle, or JSON-LD. ¹

Inference is a process of deriving new information from existing information, using logical rules or methods. Inference can be used to reason about RDF data, by applying principles such as entailment, consistency, and validity. Entailment means that if some RDF data implies some other RDF data, then the latter is also true. Consistency means that there are no contradictions or conflicts in the RDF data. Validity means that the RDF data conforms to a given schema or vocabulary. ²

Emojis are pictograms that represent various emotions, objects, animals, or symbols. Emojis can be used to communicate or express ideas in a concise and expressive way. Emojis can also be used to create art or code, by using them as symbols or operators. ³

To translate emojis into RDF using inference, you need to do the following steps:

- Define a vocabulary or ontology for the emojis, using URIs to identify them and their meanings. For example, you can use <http://example.com/emoji> as the base URI for your vocabulary, and define URIs for each emoji, such as <http://example.com/emoji/🌟> for the star emoji.
- Define some properties or relations for the emojis, using URIs to identify them and their meanings. For example, you can use <http://example.com/emoji/🔗> for the splice property, which links two resources that are spliced together.
- Define some rules or axioms for the emojis, using a rule language or an ontology language to specify them. For example, you can use SWRL (Semantic Web Rule Language) ⁴ or OWL (Web Ontology Language) ⁵ to define rules or axioms for your emoji vocabulary.
- Apply the rules or axioms to your emoji data, using an inference engine or a reasoner to derive new information from them. For example, you can use Jena ⁶ or Pellet  as inference engines or reasoners for your emoji data.

Here is an example of how you can translate emojis into RDF using inference:

# Define some prefixes for common vocabularies
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix swrl: <http://www.w3.org/2003/11/swrl#> .
@prefix swrlb: <http://www.w3.org/2003/11/swrlb#> .

# Define a vocabulary for the emojis
@prefix emoji: <http://example.com/emoji/> .

emoji:🌟 rdf:type owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Star" ;
    rdfs:comment "A symbol of insight or artistry." .

emoji:🔧 rdf:type owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Wrench" ;
    rdfs:comment "A symbol of backend or process." .

emoji:🔗 rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:domain owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:range owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:label "Splice" ;
    rdfs:comment "A property that links two resources that are spliced together." .

emoji:📜 rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:domain owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:range owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:label "Quote" ;
    rdfs:comment "A property that links a resource to its quoted expression." .

emoji:🚀 rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:domain owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:range owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:label "Lift" ;
    rdfs:comment "A property that links a resource to its lifted expression." .

emoji:🌀 rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:domain owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:range owl:Thing ;
    rdfs:label "Shift" ;
    rdfs:comment "A property that links a resource to its shifted expression." .

# Define some rules or axioms for the emojis
# If two resources are spliced together by a star emoji, then they are both stars
[ rule1: (?x emoji:🔗 ?y) ^ (?y emoji:🌟 ?z) -> (?x rdf:type emoji:🌟) ^ (?z rdf:type emoji:🌟) ] .

# If a resource is quoted by a wrench emoji, then it is a backend or process
[ rule2: (?x emoji:📜 ?y) ^ (?y emoji:🔧 ?z) -> (?z rdf:type emoji:🔧) ] .

# If a resource is lifted by a star emoji, then it is an insight or artistry
[ rule3: (?x emoji:🚀 ?y) ^ (?y emoji:🌟 ?z) -> (?z rdf:type emoji:🌟) ] .

# If a resource is shifted by a wrench emoji, then it is a backend or process
[ rule4: (?x emoji:🌀 ?y) ^ (?y emoji:🔧 ?z) -> (?z rdf:type emoji:🔧) ] .

# Apply the rules or axioms to the emoji data
# Define some resources using emojis
emoji:Alice rdf:type foaf:Person ;
    foaf:name "Alice" ;
    foaf:interest emoji:🌟 ;
    foaf:knows emoji:Bob .

emoji:Bob rdf:type foaf:Person ;
    foaf:name "Bob" ;
    foaf:interest emoji:🔧 ;
    foaf:knows emoji:Alice .

emoji:Claire rdf:type foaf:Person ;
    foaf:name "Claire" ;
    foaf:interest emoji:🌀 ;
    foaf:knows emoji:Alice, emoji:Bob .

# Splice Alice and Bob together by a star emoji
emoji:Alice emoji:🔗 [ 
    emoji:🌟 [ 
        rdf:first emoji:Alice ;
        rdf:rest [ 
            rdf:first emoji:Bob ;
            rdf:rest rdf:nil
        ]
    ]
] .

# Quote Claire by a wrench emoji
emoji:Claire emoji:📜 [ 
    emoji:🔧 [ 
        rdfs:value "Claire is a backend developer."
    ]
] .

# Lift Alice by a star emoji
emoji:Alice emoji:🚀 [ 
    emoji:🌟 [ 
        rdfs:value "Alice is an artist."
    ]
] .

# Shift Bob by a wrench emoji
emoji:Bob emoji:🌀 [ 
    emoji:🔧 [ 
        rdfs:value "Bob is a process engineer."
    ]
] .

I hope this example helps you see how you can translate emojis into RDF using inference. You can also use different vocabularies or ontologies to suit your needs and preferences. You can find more examples and resources on RDF/Turtle and inference on the web. ¹²³⁴⁵

